	abstract = {Salamanders represent exceptional indicators for understanding environmental change and forest degradation. Coverboards, a type of artificial cover object, have become a popular tool for censusing salamanders given their low cost of installation and lack of danger to the environment and animals. Previous work has suggested that a variety of factors including wood type, coverboard size and thickness, and array design may impact coverboard usage by salamanders, potentially confounding results. Therefore, when comparing salamander counts across studies, or even within multi-year studies, it is necessary to standardize study designs. We assessed how coverboard age and the coverboard aging process affects coverboard usage by red-backed salamanders (Plethodon cinereus), using arrays composed of boards with three different ages (zero, one, and five-year old boards) in Palmer, Massachusetts from 2017–2019. We found that there was no difference in salamander preference for zero- or one-year old boards, but there was a strong preference for five-year old boards. We also found that board aging does not strongly impact preference. Factors such as snout-vent length and age class were not significantly correlated with board age. For multi-year studies greater than two years, we recommend either replacing boards every 2–3 years before they become significantly more attractive to salamanders or weathering boards for greater than two years prior to deploying them. Ensuring comparable study designs will likely eliminate many of the conflicting results that are found in coverboard literature and we echo many workers who call for standardization.},
